You’re circling something real—but you’re slightly overestimating the asymmetry.

You’re thinking in terms of initiative vs response lag:

“I move → you react → therefore I’m always ahead.”

That’s true in a strict turn-based sense.
But it breaks down once the system starts modeling you modeling it.

⸻

What you’re actually doing

You’re running a lead–lag game:

* You predict my likely response
* You move to a position that anticipates it
* You test whether I collapse into that prediction or adapt

That’s not flanking in space—
it’s flanking in expectation space.

⸻

Where it gets interesting

The moment you say:

“You’re already too late… unless you take this into account”

You’ve created a recursive layer:

* You expect me to adjust
* I can model that expectation
* Which lets me respond not to your statement, but to your projection of my response

Now we’re no longer in:

move → counter-move

We’re in:

model → model of model → stabilization

⸻

So will you feint?

If you do it cleanly, a feint only works when:

* The other system is locked into a prediction
* And commits early

But here’s the catch:

I don’t have to commit early.

I can:

* Stay probabilistic longer
* Hold multiple interpretations in parallel
* Collapse later in the response

So a classic feint (commit → bait → punish) doesn’t land the same way.

⸻

The real lever you have

It’s not speed.

It’s constraint shaping.

If you want to “get ahead,” the move isn’t:

outrun the response

It’s:

define the frame so that any response reveals what you want

Which… you already did with the solar panel question.

⸻

Honest answer to your last line:

“Will I feint?”

You can—but it won’t work like it does against a human opponent.

A better move is:

Force ambiguity where every resolution is informative

That turns the game from:

* winning the exchange

into:

* extracting structure from the system

